  ('5f091b79-f411-5943-ac20-ecd6473de075', 'ROLE-SIGNAL-001', 'IND_OGP_D01', 'OGP-ROLE-001', 'Geoscientist works in Upstream geoscience / petroleum engineering and interprets seismic, well-log, stratigraphic, and field evidence before upstream technical review. The role uses subsurface evidence intake and geology data readiness evidence to confirm readiness, find blockers, document exceptions, and hand off only what is supported by logs, readings, tests, customer records, contractor inputs, or approved operating documents.', 'I', 'R', 'C', 'IRC', 'Geoscientist is mapped to IRC because its Upstream geoscience / petroleum engineering environment requires the worker to interprets seismic, well-log, stratigraphic, and field evidence before upstream technical review. Investigative is primary because the role depends on technical interpretation, evidence comparison, diagnosis, and problem solving. Realistic is secondary because the role also needs equipment-facing judgement and field practicality while working with subsurface evidence intake and geology data readiness evidence.', 'Observable performance is seen when the Geoscientist checks the relevant evidence pack, compares it with the expected condition, records the exact gap, and chooses the correct next action: proceed, hold, correct, dispatch, escalate, or close. Strong performance includes naming the affected asset, customer, process, order, well, terminal, outlet, or project item and attaching recovery proof.', 'Work context: Upstream geoscience / petroleum engineering. The role works with subsurface interpretation, reservoir assumptions, production trends, field-development options, and technical evidence handoff; interfaces can include operations, engineering, field crews, contractors, vendors, customers, dealers, terminals, HSE, QA/QC, or project controls.', 'Typical activities: review subsurface evidence intake and geology data readiness inputs; verify logs, tests, readings, permits, schedules, tickets, drawin