ition because the work involves interpreting vehicle, battery, charging, plant, service, channel, or mobility records, comparing evidence, detecting exceptions, and deciding the correct handoff or closure route. Lower readiness in mandatory areas should trigger bridge practice rather than automatic rejection unless the role is safety, license, or authority gated."}'::jsonb, '{"traits": ["Conscientiousness", "Agreeableness", "Emotional Stability"], "rationale": "Systems Engineer benefits from conscientiousness, agreeableness, emotional stability because the role requires disciplined evidence handling, coordination across engineering/commercial/service owners, and steady follow-up under launch, quality, customer, uptime, or compliance pressure. These traits should adjust confidence and coaching focus, not act as a hard exclusion rule."}'::jsonb, '{"values": ["Impact", "Security", "Financial Growth"], "rationale": "Systems Engineer aligns best with learners who value impact, security, financial growth because the role environment involves visible product/service impact, reliable operations, ownership of follow-up, and commercially or technically accountable outcomes. Work values should be used to prioritise role options, not to prove technical ability."}'::jsonb, 'Preferred', 'Mechanical; Electrical; Electronics; Automobile; Mechatronics; Production; Industrial; Chemical; Data/IT depending on role', true),
